<article class="methodology-page">
  <div class="container">

    <h1>Methodology: How the Business Valuation Calculator Works</h1>
    <p class="methodology-updated">Last updated: {{ site.dataLastModified }} · Data: {{ site.dataSource }}</p>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>Data Source</h2>
      <p>
        All industry multiples used in this calculator are derived from the
        <a href="{{ site.bizBuySellUrl }}" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BizBuySell Industry Valuation Report</a>,
        published by CoStar Group. BizBuySell is the largest business-for-sale marketplace in the United
        States and publishes closed transaction data - verified sale prices from completed transactions,
        not asking prices or broker estimates.
      </p>
      <p>
        The dataset underlying this calculator covers <strong>{{ site.transactionCount }}+ closed transactions</strong>
        from Q1 {{ site.dataCoverageStart }} through Q4 {{ site.dataCoverageEnd }}, across 63 industries
        in 12 categories. Transactions are weighted toward the most recent four quarters to reflect
        current market conditions while maintaining statistical stability in industries with lower
        transaction volumes.
      </p>
      <p>
        BizBuySell data covers businesses primarily in the Main Street segment - those with revenue
        under approximately $10M. It does not represent mid-market or large-cap business transactions,
        which are reported through different channels (Capital IQ, PitchBook, etc.) and use different
        valuation metrics (EBITDA multiples rather than SDE multiples).
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>What the Multiples Represent</h2>
      <p>
        For each of the 63 industries in the dataset, we report three SDE multiple points and one
        revenue multiple:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lower Quartile (sde_multiple_low):</strong> The 25th percentile of closed transaction multiples for this industry. Approximately 25% of transactions in this industry closed at or below this multiple.</li>
        <li><strong>Median (sde_multiple_mid):</strong> The 50th percentile. Half of transactions closed above this multiple; half below. This is the primary reference point for the base valuation.</li>
        <li><strong>Upper Quartile (sde_multiple_high):</strong> The 75th percentile. Approximately 25% of transactions closed at or above this multiple.</li>
        <li><strong>Revenue Multiple (revenue_multiple_avg):</strong> The average ratio of sale price to annual revenue across closed transactions. Used as a secondary reference check, not a primary valuation method for most Main Street businesses.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These are not theoretical multiples derived from comparable analysis or broker estimates.
        They are observed ratios from actual reported transaction prices.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>Base Calculation</h2>
      <p>
        The calculator's base calculation applies the industry-specific lower quartile and upper quartile
        multiples to the user's stated annual SDE:
      </p>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <p><code>base_low  = sde_multiple_low × annual_sde</code></p>
        <p><code>base_high = sde_multiple_high × annual_sde</code></p>
      </div>
      <p>
        This produces an unadjusted range representing where comparable businesses in this industry
        have traded, before accounting for the specific quality and risk characteristics of the
        user's business.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>Adjustment Factors</h2>
      <p>
        Three adjustment factors shift the base multiple range up or down based on the user's inputs.
        Each factor represents a documented driver of multiple variation in Main Street transaction data.
      </p>

      <h3>Revenue Trend</h3>
      <p>
        Revenue growth trajectory is one of the strongest predictors of whether a business sells
        at the upper or lower end of its industry range. Buyers pay for momentum; they discount for
        uncertainty.
      </p>
      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Selection</th><th>Adjustment (applied to both low and high)</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Growing 20%+/yr</td><td>+0.30×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Growing 10–20%/yr</td><td>+0.15×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Flat (±5%)</td><td>0×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Declining</td><td>−0.25×</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>Owner Involvement</h3>
      <p>
        Owner dependency is the most common discount factor in Main Street acquisitions. Businesses
        where the owner is the primary service provider, holds key customer relationships, or manages
        all daily operations require buyers to price in the cost and risk of replacing that involvement.
        Systematized businesses - where operations run via trained staff and documented processes  -
        transfer more reliably and command higher prices.
      </p>
      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Selection</th><th>Adjustment</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Low - mostly runs without me</td><td>+0.20×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Moderate - some systems, but I'm still key</td><td>0×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>High - I'm central to daily operations</td><td>−0.20×</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>Customer Concentration</h3>
      <p>
        Customer concentration - a single customer representing a disproportionate share of revenue  -
        is a primary SBA lender risk flag. If the concentrated customer departs post-acquisition,
        the earnings base that supported the purchase price may no longer exist. Buyers and their
        lenders apply meaningful discounts for concentration risk.
      </p>
      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Selection</th><th>Adjustment</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Diverse - no single customer over 15%</td><td>+0.10×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Concentrated - one or a few customers 40%+</td><td>−0.25×</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>Combined Adjustment Application</h3>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <p><code>total_adjustment = revenue_adj + owner_adj + concentration_adj</code></p>
        <p><code>adjusted_low  = base_low  + (total_adjustment × annual_sde / base_multiple... </code></p>
      </div>
      <p>
        More precisely: the adjustment is applied to the <em>multiple</em>, not directly to the dollar value,
        then the adjusted multiple is applied to SDE:
      </p>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <p><code>adjusted_multiple_low  = sde_multiple_low  + total_adjustment</code></p>
        <p><code>adjusted_multiple_high = sde_multiple_high + total_adjustment</code></p>
        <p><code>valuation_low  = adjusted_multiple_low  × annual_sde</code></p>
        <p><code>valuation_high = adjusted_multiple_high × annual_sde</code></p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>Floor and Ceiling Rules</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Floor:</strong> The adjusted multiple cannot fall below 1.0×. A business rarely sells
        for less than one year of earnings, regardless of risk factors, because sellers have the option
        to simply continue operating. Results are floored at <code>max(adjusted_multiple, 1.0) × SDE</code>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Ceiling note:</strong> When the adjusted high multiple exceeds 6.0×, the calculator
        displays a contextual note: "This estimate reflects strong transaction multiples in your industry.
        Multiples above 6× are rare and typically apply to businesses with significant recurring revenue
        and minimal owner dependency." The calculation is not capped - the note provides context.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>Revenue Multiple (Secondary Check)</h2>
      <p>
        The calculator also computes a revenue-based valuation using the industry's average revenue
        multiple from the BizBuySell dataset:
      </p>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <p><code>revenue_valuation = revenue_multiple_avg × annual_revenue</code></p>
      </div>
      <p>
        This is displayed as a secondary reference, not the primary output. For most Main Street
        businesses, the SDE-based range is the governing metric. The revenue-based estimate provides
        a market sanity check - significant divergence between the two figures (SDE-based estimate
        much higher or lower than revenue-based) may indicate unusual margin characteristics worth
        investigating.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>Rounding</h2>
      <p>
        All dollar output values are rounded to the nearest $5,000. False precision is noise for
        planning purposes. "$382,417" is not more useful than "$380,000" - it implies a precision
        the underlying data does not support.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>What This Calculator Is Not</h2>
      <p>
        This calculator produces planning estimates - not formal appraisals. Key limitations:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Not a formal business appraisal.</strong> A formal appraisal requires on-site
          inspection, detailed financial analysis, and attestation by a certified valuator (CVA, ABV,
          or ASA). The output of this calculator cannot be used for legal, tax, estate, financing,
          or litigation purposes.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Not a broker opinion of value.</strong> An experienced broker applies market knowledge
          specific to your local market, buyer demand signals, and qualitative factors not captured in
          the six inputs of this tool.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Not predictive of any specific offer.</strong> Individual buyers have specific
          strategic or financial rationales that may cause them to bid above or below the statistical
          median for your industry. The calculator predicts where your business should trade based on
          comparable transactions - not where any specific buyer will bid.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Not a substitute for professional advice.</strong> Before listing your business for
          sale, consult with a business broker, a CPA experienced in business sales, and a transaction
          attorney. The cost of professional guidance is almost always less than the value destroyed
          by entering a sale process without it.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>Data Updates</h2>
      <p>
        Industry multiples are updated twice per year as BizBuySell releases new transaction data (typically Q2 and Q4).
        The current dataset reflects {{ site.dataSource }}.
        The <code>last_updated</code> field in each industry's data record reflects the date the
        specific industry's multiples were last refreshed.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>Questions and Corrections</h2>
      <p>
        If you identify a data discrepancy, have a question about a specific industry's multiples,
        or want to report an issue with the calculator, contact
        <a href="mailto:{{ site.contactEmail }}">{{ site.contactEmail }}</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

  </div>
</article>

